The only patron learned men have, says Juvenal, is the emperor, and it has been much quaetioned which emperor it could have been. The statement is most in accordance with what we hear of the reign of Hadrian, during which he managed to encourage the arts and literature at Rome, though he was absent the greater part of his time. The subject is discussed in the Life of Juvenal, to which the reader is referred.
